Lemma 8.12 (Rank-increasing evaluations complete). Let 7 be a -compatible con-
straint set, and let (; â€²)= p7q. If a rank-increasing evaluation of (; â€²) diverges,
then 7 has no solution.
Proof. A rank-increasing evaluation of (; â€²) induces an evaluation of Unify(7) such
that, if the evaluation of (; â€²) diverges, then the induced evaluation of Unify(7) also
diverges. By Lemma 5.11, if 7 has a solution, then every evaluation of Unify(7)
terminates. This implies the desired result.
Theorem 8.13 (Decidability of 0nite-rank beta-uni0cation). Let 7 be a -compatible
constraint set and let k be a :xed but otherwise arbitrary integer Â¿1.
1. 7 has a solution of rank 6k if and only if there is a successful evaluation of
UnifyFR(7; k).
2. There is an evaluation of UnifyFR(7; k) which terminates.
3. It is decidable whether 7 has a solution of rank 6k.
We purposely impose the restriction k =0 because, if 7 has more than one constraint
and p7q=(; â€²), then rank{; â€²}Â¿1. In such a case, an evaluation of UnifyFR(7; 0)
always fails, even if 7 has a rank-0 solution.
We conjecture part 2 of the theorem can be strengthened to: â€œEvery evaluation
of UnifyFR(7; k) terminates.â€ The conjecture will be settled if one proves that every
evaluation of a -compatible pair (0; â€²0) that diverges is rank-increasing; Lemma 8.10
proves it for only a particular evaluation strategy.
Proof. For the left-to-right implication in part 1, suppose 7 has a solution. By Theorem
5.16, Unify(7) âˆ—â‡’S for some substitution S, which is also a principal solution for 7.
The evaluation Unify(7) âˆ—â‡’S induces an evaluation UnifyFR(7; â€˜) âˆ—â‡’S for some â€˜Â¿0.
Let â€˜ be the least integer such that UnifyFR(7; â€˜) âˆ—â‡’S. Suppose S is a rank-m solution
for 7, with mÂ¿0. Because S is a principal solution for 7, every other solution is of rank
