Â¿m. If mÂ¿1, it is easy to see that â€˜=m, which also implies that UnifyFR(7; k) âˆ—â‡’S
for every kÂ¿m. (If m=0 and 7 has more than one constraint, then â€˜=1.)
For the right-to-left implication in part 1, suppose there is a successful evaluation
UnifyFR(7; k) âˆ—â‡’S for some kÂ¿0, and suppose k is the least integer with this property.
(We do not need to impose the restriction k =0 for this implication.) The evaluation
UnifyFR(7; k) âˆ—â‡’S induces an evaluation Unify(7) âˆ—â‡’S. By Theorem 5.16, S is a prin-
cipal solution for 7. Moreover, if k =0 or kÂ¿2, then S is a rank-k solution; and if
k =1, then S is of rank 6k.
We prove parts 2 and 3 of the theorem simultaneously. Let (0; â€²0)= p7q and con-
sider a rank-increasing evaluation of (0; â€²0) as speci0ed in De0nition 8.11:
(0; â€²0)
